Preprocessing the text data¶

In [4]:
#nytimes_train
nytimes_train_df = pd.DataFrame(nytimes_train)

def clean_text(text):
    # Remove non-alphanumeric characters and convert to lowercase
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z\s]', '', text.lower())
    return text

def remove_stopwords(text):
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    word_tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    filtered_text = [word for word in word_tokens if word not in stop_words]
    return filtered_text

def lemmatize_text(text):
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmatized_text = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in text]
    return lemmatized_text

# Apply preprocessing to relevant textual features
textual_features = ['headline', 'article', 'abstract', 'caption']
for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] = nytimes_train_df[feature].apply(clean_text)
    nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] = nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'].apply(remove_stopwords)
    nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] = nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'].apply(lemmatize_text)

# Join tokens back to text
for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] = nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x))

# Handling empty documents and replacing missing values for all textual features
for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] = nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'].replace('', pd.NA)

# Replace missing values for all textual features
nytimes_train_df.fillna('', inplace=True)

# Additional filtering step to remove empty documents after complete preprocessing for all textual features
for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_train_df = nytimes_train_df[nytimes_train_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_train'] != '']


# Display the preprocessed data
print(nytimes_train_df.head())

#nytimes_test
nytimes_test_df = pd.DataFrame(nytimes_test)

def clean_text(text):
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z\s]', '', text.lower())
    return text

def remove_stopwords(text):
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    word_tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    filtered_text = [word for word in word_tokens if word not in stop_words]
    return filtered_text

def lemmatize_text(text):
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    lemmatized_text = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in text]
    return lemmatized_text

textual_features = ['headline', 'article', 'abstract', 'caption']
for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] = nytimes_test_df[feature].apply(clean_text)
    nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] = nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'].apply(remove_stopwords)
    nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] = nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'].apply(lemmatize_text)

for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] = nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join(x))

for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] = nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'].replace('', pd.NA)

nytimes_test_df.fillna('', inplace=True)

for feature in textual_features:
    nytimes_test_df = nytimes_test_df[nytimes_test_df[f'cleaned_{feature}_test'] != '']

print(nytimes_test_df.head())

In the preprocessing phase for both the training and testing datasets, I cleaned and standardized textual features. This involved removing non-alphanumeric characters, converting text to lowercase, removing stopwords, and lemmatizing words. These steps were applied to each textual feature ('headline', 'article', 'abstract', 'caption') and missing values were handled by replacing empty documents with NaN values.

Finally, I filtered out rows with empty documents post-preprocessing to ensure data integrity and uniform representation for further analysis and modeling.

def tokenize(text):
    return word_tokenize(text)

# Define the number of top words

for section, words in grouped.items():
    # Count occurrences of each word
    word_counts = Counter(words)
    # Get the top words
    top_words = word_counts.most_common(top_words_count)
    top_words_by_section[section] = top_words

# Print the top words for each section
for section, top_words in top_words_by_section.items():
    print(f"Top words in section '{section}':")
    for word, count in top_words:
        print(f"{word}: {count}")
    print()

# Apply oversampling or undersampling to balance the classes :

# Identify class distribution
class_distribution_train = nytimes_train_df['section'].value_counts()

# Set threshold for class imbalance
threshold = 1000 

# Identify minority and majority classes
minority_classes_train = class_distribution_train[class_distribution_train < threshold].index
majority_classes_train = class_distribution_train[class_distribution_train >= threshold].index

oversampler = RandomOverSampler()
undersampler = RandomUnderSampler()

X_train = nytimes_train_df.drop(columns=['section'])
y_train = nytimes_train_df['section']

if len(minority_classes_train) > 0:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = oversampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
elif len(majority_classes_train) > 0:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = undersampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
else:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = X_train, y_train

# Ensure balanced class distribution after resampling
print("Class distribution after resampling for section class in Training dataset:")
print(y_train_resampled.value_counts())

# Apply oversampling or undersampling to balance the classes in testing dataset :

from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler

# Identify class distribution
class_distribution_test = nytimes_test_df['section'].value_counts()
threshold = 1000  

# Identify minority and majority classes
minority_classes_test = class_distribution_test[class_distribution_test < threshold].index
majority_classes_test = class_distribution_test[class_distribution_test >= threshold].index

oversampler = RandomOverSampler()
undersampler = RandomUnderSampler()

X_train = nytimes_test_df.drop(columns=['section'])
y_train = nytimes_test_df['section']

if len(minority_classes_test) > 0:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = oversampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
elif len(majority_classes_train) > 0:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = undersampler.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
else:
    X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = X_train, y_train

print("Class distribution after resampling for section class in testing dataset:")
print(y_train_resampled.value_counts())

In the data analysis and exploration step for both the training and testing datasets, I initially visualized the distribution of each section type using count plots. This provided insights into the proportion of articles belonging to different categories. Additionally, I calculated the percentages of each section type to understand their relative frequencies within the datasets.

Furthermore, I extracted the top words for each section in both datasets to identify common themes or topics. Comparing the top words between the training and testing datasets revealed similarities and differences in the most frequent terms associated with each section.

Finally, I checked for data imbalance within each dataset by examining the class distribution of section types. I applied oversampling or undersampling techniques to balance the classes, ensuring that each section type had a similar representation in the datasets.

# Container for sentences
news = np.array([headline for headline in nytimes_train_df['cleaned_headline_train']])

# Container for labels
labels = np.array([label for label in nytimes_train_df['section']])

# Tokenization
tokenizer = Tokenizer()
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(news)
word_index = tokenizer.word_index
vocab_size = len(word_index) + 1

sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(news)

# Padding
maxlen = 100  # You can adjust the maximum length of sequences as needed
padded_sequences = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=maxlen, padding='post')

# Encoding labels
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
encoded_labels = label_encoder.fit_transform(labels)

# Model Architecture
embedding_dim = 100  
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(input_dim=vocab_size, output_dim=embedding_dim))  # Removed input_length argument
model.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(64)))
model.add(Dense(len(label_encoder.classes_), activation='softmax'))

# Compile the Model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Training
model.fit(padded_sequences, encoded_labels, epochs=10, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

For modeling, I initially chose Naive Bayes because it's suitable for text classification tasks where features are assumed to be independent. However, Naive Bayes may oversimplify relationships between words. Hence, I also explored BiLSTM, a deep learning model capable of capturing complex sequential patterns in text data.

Naive Bayes yielded an accuracy of approximately 61% on the testing dataset, while BiLSTM achieved around 56%. Although Naive Bayes performed better in terms of accuracy, BiLSTM might offer more potential for capturing intricate relationships among words, albeit with longer training times.

# Given list of sentences
sentences = [

]

# Tokenize and pad the sequences
sentence_sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(sentences)
padded_sentence_sequences = pad_sequences(sentence_sequences, maxlen=maxlen, padding='post')

# Predict category labels
predicted_labels = model.predict(padded_sentence_sequences)
predicted_categories = label_encoder.inverse_transform(np.argmax(predicted_labels, axis=1))

# Print predicted category labels for each sentence
for sentence, category in zip(sentences, predicted_categories):
    print(f"Sentence: {sentence} - Predicted section: {category}")
